physical examinations and health literature. The advertised goal of the LEI was 
to extend life without old age, as well as improve masculinity and good business 
practices through adherence to health principles. The first two decades of 
activities of the Life Extension Institute offer a window for examining early 
twentieth-century ideas about the relationships between health, old age, and 
masculinity. The LEI literature constructed a picture of healthy, vigorous, and 
efficient American working men that helped to cement ideals of masculinity to 
ideals of health.

