739. Wests Calif Report. 1992 Jan 29;4:59-65.

Donaldson v. Van de Kamp.

California. Court of Appeal, Second District, Division 6.

KIE: The California Court of Appeal, Second District, held that Thomas 
Donaldson, who has an inoperable, malignant brain tumor, has no constitutional 
right to either premortem cryogenic suspension or assisted suicide. Donaldson 
claimed that his right to privacy, self determination, and free expression 
enabled him to undergo this procedure, which would irreversibly cease his 
circulatory, respiratory, and brain functions. However, the court determined 
that the state's interest in preserving life, preventing suicide, protecting 
innocent third parties, and maintaining the ethical integrity of the medical 
profession outweighed Donaldson's interest in preserving his body until 
treatment for his condition was available. The court distinguished Donaldson's 
situation from cases involving the termination of life support systems. The 
court denied Donaldson's request that a coroner be prohibited from performing an 
autopsy. The court also refused to prevent law enforcement officials from 
prosecuting any individual who assists in a suicide.

PMID: 11648224 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


740. Atl Report. 1987 Jun 24;529:419-34.

In re Peter.

New Jersey. Supreme Court.

KIE: A 65-year-old nursing home patient in a persistent vegetative state with no 
hope of recovery, Hilda Peter was sustained by a nasogastric tube and was not 
expected to die in the near future. Citing her life expectancy, the New Jersey 
Ombudsman for the Institutionalized Elderly denied her guardian's request under 
power of attorney to remove the tube in accordance with her wishes as expressed 
prior to her incompetency. The New Jersey Supreme Court granted the guardian's 
application for certification and remanded the case to the Ombudsman, thus 
affirming the right to refuse life-sustaining medical treatment, regardless of 
competency.

PMID: 11648264 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


741. All Engl Law Rep. 1981 Aug 7;[1990] 3:927-30.

Re B (A Minor) (Wardship: Medical Treatment).

Great Britain. England. Court of Appeal, Civil Division.

KIE: The British Court of Appeal, Civil Division, allowed the appeal of the 
local NHS health authority and authorized life-saving surgery for a mentally 
retarded infant against her parents' wishes. B was born with Down syndrome and 
an intestinal blockage. Without an operation, she would die within days; with an 
operation and without other complications, her life expectancy was between 20 
and 30 years. Acting in what they saw as their child's best interests, her 
parents refused to consent to the operation. The appellate court's decision to 
authorize surgery was based on the welfare of the child. The judges held that if 
the operation were successful the girl could live the normal life span of a Down 
syndrome child with the handicaps of such a child, and "it is not for this court 
to say that life of that description ought to be extinguished."

PMID: 11648312 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


742. Wests Calif Report. 1992 Aug 21;11:169-88.

Arato v. Avedon.

California. Court of Appeal, Second District, Division 3.

KIE: A California appellate court reversed a jury verdict in favor of a doctor 
who had been accused of negligence by surviving family members for not 
disclosing life expectancy information to a patient suffering from pancreatic 
cancer. The Court of Appeal determined that a physician has a fiduciary duty to 
disclose information about life expectancy to a patient who has indicated his 
desire to make a fully informed decision. In addition, the court held that 
expert testimony concerning medical community standards regarding disclosure of 
life expectancy was erroneously admitted because the duty to disclose is 
mandated by law. Also, the instructions given to the jury at the trial were 
misleading because they implied, "...the physician, not the patient, ultimately 
knows what is best...."

PMID: 11648615 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


743. Soc Sci Med F. 1981 Dec;15F(4):151-6.

Triage in medical practices: an unacceptable model?

Bell NK.

KIE: Two basic presuppositions of triage are challenged: the utilitarian notion 
that it is morally preferable to save the greater number, and the extension of 
the salvageability concept as a model for macroallocation of scarce medical 
resources. The 'more is better' principle lacks the status of a universal moral 
obligation and leads to an impersonal view of the valuing of life. In the 
allocation of scarce resources, triage is suspect since life-saving decisions 
involve medical, social, economic, and political criteria. Triage thus 
perpetuates existing injustices.

